  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Iraq: Strengthening the MDR capacity of human rights defenders</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The HURICAP project in Iraq sought to train a select group of committed human rights defenders affiliated to our local partner in the documentation of human rights violations. The aim was to raise the quality of our partner&#x2019;s human rights documentation and reporting work so that it can be effectively used to support their advocacy initiatives and Amnesty&#x2019;s research on Iraq. Violations under investigation are identified in close consultation with Amnesty&#x2019;s Iraq research team in the Beirut office and include cases of torture during demonstrations, enforced disappearances and sexual violence in conflict areas.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Iraqi armed conflict began with the 2003 invasion of Iraq by a United States-led coalition that led to the fall of the government of Saddam Hussein. The conflict continued as an insurgency to oppose, amongst others, the country&#x2019;s occupying forces and the Iraqi government that was established after Hussein&#x2019;s fall. The expansion of Islamic State in 2014, followed by the international response to counter this development, further drew the country into instability and violence. Violence in Iraq is multifaceted with intensity and type varying across the country&#x2019;s different regions. It can be political, tribal, sectarian and intra-sectarian, or linked to insurgency, terrorism, military operations or organized crime. It goes hand in hand with widespread human rights violations and abuses by all parties to the conflict(s).

In October 2019, nationwide protests started, demanding better employment opportunities, public services, an end to government corruption, and even the fall of the government. Protestors were confronted with excessive force by security forces, and subjected to arrest, enforced disappearance and other forms of intimidation.</narrative>
  </description>
